metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #65
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Entrecroisement #76
metadata.description:
"Entrecroisement" is a French word meaning "intersections".
In this project, colored lines travel like rays of light that are reflected 
on the inner walls of a shape of a form in which it cannot exit. The different 
shapes are born (or filled) from these intersections.

The rendering time can take up to a minute
some parameters are adjustable with fx(params) and others are fixed according to the seeds 

To save a png file at 1500x2000 px type [s]

To render at 3000x4000 px resolution type [1] then press [s] 
type [2] to render at 4500x6000 px (can be long !)
---
100% done with p5js
some palettes comes from Werner's Nomenclature of Colors
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
---
Hervé ( mars 23)

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 3 #179
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Solitude Meditation #25
metadata.description:
"A room, a space, a solitude corner within the inner thought. Existed as a place to meditate and replenish the soul to be more at ease."

This piece means to mimic a sense of a dark room that contains radiated warm lights with subtle movement. It will follow the current resolution of the window where it is placed.

/////INTERACTIVITY/////
Do all the instructions below after opening the live mode.

1. To capture the screen, press the "c" button on your computer keyboard.

2. To save a 3-second .GIF from your iteration, press the "s" button on your computer keyboard. Please be patient while waiting for the piece to save and render its frames.

3. To adjust the piece resolution, you need to set your browser first and then reload the browser every time you want to capture the screen or save the rendered .GIF file.
///////////////////////

Created using Hydra and p5.js

Rangga Purnama Aji, 2022
https://linktr.ee/ranggapuraji

metadata.name: The Unrealized Painting #48
metadata.description:
Click to start.

The size of the canvas is proportional to the monitor. You can scale up using 1,2,3 and 4 of you keyboard to increase the quality of resolution (it may create some variations on the art itself, and it should be done before clicking on canvas)

The preview is only a sketch of the artwork, since the livecoding functions vary depending on the interaction.

This project was designed in Hydra.js for Desktop computers on Chrome.

Since it is a livecoding library there may be small differences in each code execution, but the deterministic character remains.

The machine waits for your command to start drawing - there is no plan or goal, sometimes the values assigned to the variables would lead to the construction of a visually recognizable work, but the fact that these values are randomized 4 times during the duration of the interaction breaks the logical line of visual conduction.

I can only appeal to Gestalt, and beg you to make the effort to see the whole divided between 4 apparently disconnected patterns. This is not just a code that generates noises, I am here making a testament to push once again the limit of abstraction, to perhaps convince you that there is immense beauty in discontinuity.

And it is worth commenting once again that without your click/command, the machine will be eternally lodged in the server waiting - and not knowing what it is waiting for. And this waiting is the most beautiful thing in the world, because the art is already determined to happen, its strokes and patterns were defined when the hash was tied to the code, the art was already made and already exists in the moment preceding this one - but for a computer time does not exist.

The Unrealized Painting has come to remind you that we, the ones with souls and who feel time, control the realizable and the unrealizable - and it will never stop being that way.

metadata.name: Machine Spirit #101
metadata.description:
Machine Spirit picks up where Equilibrium and Equanimity left off. Notwithstanding my love for generative mountains, trees, and (especially) cities, my personal artistic quest remains to produce an algorithm that generates convincing abstract art in the style of Richter and Rothko. The project you are looking at is my best attempt yet.

Trigger warning: some iterations produce rapidly flashing colors which may pose a risk of seizure to people with photosensitive epilepsy or similar conditions.

While the final result is a static image, the live view visualizes how the image is generated. It goes something like this: you start with a grid of cells in random colors, and you feed that into a carefully customized cellular automaton, where the color of each cell is determined by the color of that cell and its neighbours in the previous generation. If you end up with a single color over-powering all the others, or too many different fragmented colors, you start over. But when you reach a stable state with two or three colors, you have achieved your goal: a mathematical balance in color and composition that tends to be aesthetically pleasing as well. You then select a suitable canvas color and run a more computationally intensive rendering process, which makes the end result look more like physical paint on canvas, while retaining the subtle traces of its digital origins.

Press [b]leed, [c]anvas or [d]ensity in the live view to cycle through variations, or [p]rint to save a high resolution capture.

All iterations eventually converge to a stable state, but in theory this could last arbitrarily long, and on rare occasions it may take longer than 5 minutes, in which case the captured preview will be different from the final result. This artwork is fully generative and was hand-coded in 7,500 characters of plain JavaScript code. I didn't use any libraries, but I did take inspiration from an essay by Tyler Hobbs on polygon deformation techniques.

Forever limited to 250 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I truly hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.

metadata.name: Treasured Quilt #42
metadata.description:
Features 20 Palettes:
15 Common (6% Chance) 
Aquatic, Blue Neon, Cadets, Cadiz, Cannes, Capuccino, Flames, Futuristic, Groovy, Marrakesh, Neon, Neon Greys, Popsicle, Retro, Rustic
5 Rare (2% Chance)
Beach Huts, Heirloom, Monochrome, Preloved, Red and Greys 

Granulation Chance:
4% Chance of Ultra High Granulation
20% Chance of Low Granulation
76% Chance of High Granulation

6 Different Grid Sizes
7x7, 8x8, 9x9, 10x10, 11x11, or 12x12

102 possible background colors including circa 14% of Black and 14% of White 
Remaining 72% determined by the palette type

metadata.name: The String #330
metadata.description:
|| Anniversary project for FX(hash) 1st birthday ||

Each virtual object consists of 365 lights.
Each light represents one day of the year.

We go through every single day, thinking it's all crucial. Yet, from a perspective, it all gets compressed into a single thread. Some of the events are brighter and more memorable. Others just blend or fade away.

I welcomed November 2021 with huge excitement and celebration. The joyful beginning of the month was followed by weeks of misery, anxiety, denial, and acceptance. It was a hard time, but in the long run, it was liberating and started a process of change. Change that happens dynamically to this day.

I couldn't join you last year, but I'm celebrating with you today!



In memory of my Dad.



Donations:
40% – Savepakistan - Flood Relief Fundraiser
10% – Three.js
